{"type":"message","id":"816e575a","parentId":"9f430f34","timestamp":"2026-06-28T19:30:03.715Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":" 响应The user is saying that after the speed test completes, the result area still shows:\n```\n项目 支持 范围\n0 N -~-\n1 N -~-\n...\n```\n\nThis is clearly the **function detection** table format, not speed. The user is seeing a stale/old result from a different test. Let me check the \"一键检测\" (one-click detection) flow — that's where `renderConnectFullResults` is called, and it's likely where the issue is.\n\nThe problem might be:\n1. The speed results from the old cache still have the old format (array instead of object)\n2. The `renderConnectFullResults` speed branch expects `results.speed_map` etc.\n3. But perhaps the issue is that the user ran the speed test from a different page/button\n\nWait, actually let me look more carefully. The \"项目 支持 范围\" table with \"0 N -~-\" format is **function detection** results, not speed. This means the page is showing old function results when it should show speed.\n\nLet me check `renderConnectFullResults` — the thing is, that function renders ALL results in series (it appends). So if function was previously run and the result area wasn't cleared, both function AND speed results would show.\n\nBut actually the user said \"速度测试完成，测试结果区域依然是这样显示的\" — meaning after speed test completes, they see the stale function table. This could mean `renderConnectFullResults` has a speed branch that renders correctly but the old function table is also still displayed.\n\nActually, looking at `renderConnectFullResults` more carefully at line 1264-1320, the `connectFullResultArea` only uses `innerHTML += html` (append), so old results accumulate. That's a design choice. But the user is specifically asking about the speed display.\n\nWait, let me re-read the user's complaint. They show:\n```\n项目 支持 范围\n0 N -~-\n1 N -~-\n...\n```\n\nThis is the function detection table format (`<th>功能</th><th>支持</th><th>最小值</th>...`). This means after \"速度检测完成\", the speed section in `renderConnectFullResults` rendered nothing useful (because the old code expected `results.speed_map` but got array), while the function section still shows.\n\nBut I already fixed this! The router now returns `{speed_map, pan_speed, tilt_speed, by_zoom}` format. So the frontend `renderConnectFullResults` should now work with the speed branch.\n\nUnless... the issue is that the speed test is returning success=false (because no limit data, or HOME preset failure), and the frontend error handling only shows toast but doesn't update the result area properly.\n\nLet me check: `connectSpeedTestRun` on error shows `connectSpeedResultMini` with error text, but does it then call `renderConnectFullResults`? No — on error it only sets the mini area, not the full results area. So the full results area still shows old function detection data from a previous run. That's one issue.\n\nBut the user said \"速度测试完成\" — they see the success message from speed test but no speed data in the table. Let me check what happens in the one-click detection flow, which calls both function and speed:\n\n```\nrunDetectionStep() → calls /advanced/speed/run → renderConnectFullResults(resp.results, 'speed')\n```\n\nAnd then:\n```\nstate.results.speed = resp.results\n```\n\nSo the cached state gets `resp.results` which is the formatted object from router. But `renderConnectFullResults` now has the `by_zoom` and speed rendering code. If the formatted results are empty (`speed_map:{}, pan_speed:{}, tilt_speed:{}, by_zoom:{}`), then `_renderSpeedTable` returns empty string for each, and only \"测试总数: 0\" shows.\n\nActually, the real question is: **does the speed test actually return data?** The `run_all_tests` function needs:\n1. limit.json (from limit_data) — if not present, returns `[]`\n2. direction_info in limit_data — if missing, returns `[]`\n\nIf the user hasn't run limit test, speed test will silently fail with `[]`.\n\nThis is the most likely cause. Let me check if the router handles this case properly — it checks `isinstance(results, list) and len(results) > 0` which would be `False`, so `success=False` and `results={}`. \n\nBut the user says the test says \"速度测试完成\" but shows no data. So the message says \"速度测试完成\" but `success=false`. Wait — I changed the success check:\n\n```python\nsuccess = isinstance(results, list) and len(results) > 0\n```\n\nIf results is `[]`, success=False. And the message is `f\"速度测试完成: {req.device_ip}\"` regardless. So the frontend shows \"速度测试完成\" toast from `resp.message`, but `resp.success` is false. Then it shows \"测试失败\" toast.\n\nWait, the user says they see the toast AND the result area shows stale data. Let me look at these two paths:\n\n**Path 1: Advanced page speed test (speedTestRun)**\n- On success: `renderSpeedResults(resp.results || {})` — renders to `speedResultArea`\n- On failure: shows error in `speedResultArea`\n\n**Path 2: \"连接设备\" page speed test (connectSpeedTestRun)**\n- On success: `renderConnectSpeedResultMini` + `renderConnectFullResults` \n- On failure: shows error in `connectSpeedResultMini`\n\nThe user's screenshot shows a full table with \"项目 支持 范围\" headers, which is `renderConnectFullResults(..., 'function')` output. This means:\n1. User ran \"一键检测\" or function test first, got function results\n2. Then ran speed test, which failed (likely no limit data), but the old function results are still in `connectFullResultArea` (because it uses `innerHTML +=`)\n\nLet me also check if the \"advanced\" page speed test has the same issue. Looking at `speedTestRun` in the advanced page:\n- It clears `speedResultArea` before test\n- On success: renders speed results\n- On failure: shows error\n\nThis should work correctly now. The \"advanced\" page (independent speed test) and \"连接设备\" page are different paths.\n\nOK actually I think the real issue might be simpler. The user may have cached old speed data. Let me check the `advanced_speed_status` endpoint — does it return the cached format?\n\nLet me also check if the `store.save_speed_results` writes the formatted data or the raw list. Looking at router.py:\n```python\nstore.save_speed_results(mac_clean, results)\n```\nThis saves `results` which is the raw list from `run_all_tests()`. Then when loading from cache via `advanced_speed_status`, it returns this raw list. But the frontend for `advanced_speed_status` might pass this through `renderSpeedResults` which expects the formatted format.\n\nActually, the main issue: let me look at what `results` actually is. `run_all_tests()` returns `all_results` which is `post_process_csv(...)` — a list of dicts. So the raw format is correct but it's the `run_speed_test()` standalone function that reads cache and returns `{**cached, \"from_cache\": True}`. If cache was written as list format by a previous version, loading it now returns list format which won't match frontend expectations.\n\nAlso, `store.save_speed_results(mac_clean, results)` saves the raw list (before formatting). When `advanced_speed_status` loads cached data, it returns the raw list which the frontend can't handle.\n\nLet me focus on the actual issue: the user is on the \"高级功能\" → \"连接设备\" page and ran speed test. The result area shows the function detection table because:\n1. Speed test produced empty results (no limit data → `run_all_tests` returns `[]`)\n2. `results = []` → `success = False` → frontend shows error but old function data still shown\n\nOR:\n1. Speed test ran and produced results  \n2. `renderConnectFullResults` was called\n3. The speed branch in `renderConnectFullResults` now includes `_renderSpeedByZoom` but the data in `results.by_zoom` might be empty because the zoom key is integer and JS object iteration might have issues\n\nLet me look at the by_zoom structure more carefully:\n```python\nby_zoom.setdefault(zoom, {}).setdefault(axis, {})[sl] = sv\n```\n\nWhere `zoom = r.get(\"zoom\", 0)` — integer. In the results dict, this becomes `{10: {...}, 165: {...}, 320: {...}}` in Python. When JSON-serialized and deserialized in JS, integer keys become string keys `{\"10\": {...}, \"165\": {...}, \"320\": {...}}`. So `Object.keys(byZoom)` works fine in JS.\n\nBut the inner structure: `{10: {pan: {1: 0.23, 50: 11.5, ...}, tilt: {1: 0.15, ...}}}`. Wait — `setdefault(axis, {})[sl] = sv` — but `sl = str(r.get(\"speed_level\", 0))`. For the same `(zoom, axis, sl)` combination appearing multiple times (different directions), the later value overwrites the first. Because we use `[sl] = sv` not `.append(sv)`. \n\nSo `by_zoom` only has one direction's value per (zoom, axis, speed_level). For speed_map/pan_speed/tilt_speed we average both directions, but for by_zoom we overwrite. That's a bug but a minor one — both directions should produce similar speed.\n\nOK wait, let me re-examine. `r` from `post_process_csv` has `direction: 1 or -1`. For the same `axis=pan, zoom=10, speed_level=50`, there are two entries: one with `direction=1` and one with `direction=-1`. In the by_zoom loop:\n```python\nzoom = r.get(\"zoom\", 0)   # 10\naxis = r.get(\"axis\", \"\")   # \"pan\"  \nsl = str(r.get(\"speed_level\", 0))  # \"50\"\nsv = r.get(\"speed_val\", 0.0)  # e.g. 11.5 for direction=1\nby_zoom.setdefault(10, {}).setdefault(\"pan\", {})[\"50\"] = 11.5\n# Next entry: direction=-1, sv=11.3\nby_zoom.setdefault(10, {}).setdefault(\"pan\", {})[\"50\"] = 11.3  # overwrites 11.5\n```\n\nSo by_zoom only keeps the last direction's value per (zoom, axis, speed_level). That's fine for display.\n\nBut the main question remains: why is the user seeing stale function data?\n\nLet me think about this differently. The user says after speed test, the result still shows \"项目 支持 范围\" — that's the function test table. And each row is \"0 N -~-\". This is the renderConnectFullResults function branch. \n\nBut wait — after my fix, `renderConnectFullResults` for speed type looks different. It now has:\n```js\n} else if (type === 'speed') {\n    var byZoom = results.by_zoom || {};\n    if (byZoom && Object.keys(byZoom).length > 0) {\n        html += _renderSpeedByZoom(byZoom);\n    }\n    var speedMap = results.speed_map || results.speed_mapping || {};\n    html += _renderSpeedTable(...);\n    ...\n}\n```\n\nIf `results.speed_map` is empty `{}`, then `_renderSpeedTable` returns empty string (keys.length === 0 → ''). If `results.by_zoom` is also empty, same thing. So the speed section would show empty tables + total_tests = 0. The function table is still there from the previous run (because `innerHTML +=`).\n\nThe fix needed:\n1. Clear the full result area before appending new results\n2. Also need to ensure that if the speed test fails/succeeds with empty results, we still show something useful\n\nActually, let me look at the one-click detection (`runDetectionStep`) which calls function → then limit → then speed:\n\n```\nrunDetectionStep() {\n    url: '/advanced/function/run' → renderConnectFullResults(results.function, 'function')\n    url: '/advanced/limit/run' → renderConnectFullResults(results.limit, 'limit')  \n    url: '/advanced/speed/run' → renderConnectFullResults(results.speed, 'speed')\n}\n```\n\nEach appends to `connectFullResultArea`. So function appears first, then limit, then speed. If speed produces empty results, only \"测试总数: 0\" shows appended after the limit section.\n\nBut the user sees ONLY the function table. So maybe speed ran and the results object was `{}` (empty dict since it was a list, but the success check passed), and the old function data from a previous run was still in the page.\n\nActually, I think there's a cache issue. Let me check `advanced_speed_status` - does it return old cached data in the wrong format?\n\nLet me look at the render function more carefully. When `results` is passed into `renderConnectFullResults(results, 'speed')`, `results` comes from `resp.results` which is the formatted dict from the router. But wait - the user's `connectSpeedTestRun` also calls `renderConnectSpeedResultMini(resp.results || {})`:\n\n```js\nfunction renderConnectSpeedResultMini(results) {\n    var area = document.getElementById('connectSpeedResultMini');\n    var speedMap = results.speed_map || results.speed_mapping || {};\n    var count = Object.keys(speedMap).length;\n    var total = results.total_tests || '--';\n    area.innerHTML = '<span>✅ ' + count + ' 个速度档位 (' + total + ' 项测试)</span>';\n}\n```\n\nThis would show \"✅ 0 个速度档位 (0 项测试)\" if speed_map is empty.\n\nOK, let me just directly test what the speed test API actually returns right now for a connected device by looking at real data.\n\nActually, I think I need to trace the issue differently. Let me check the includes/advanced.html to see if there's multiple render paths.\n\nActually the simplest thing: the user probably ran the speed test from the \"高级功能\" page (not \"连接设备\" page), which uses `speedTestRun()` → `renderSpeedResults()` → `speedResultArea`, or the user was on the \"连接设备\" tab in \"高级功能\" and clicked \"速度检测\" there.\n\nThe key question: did the speed test actually produce data? Let me check if limit data exists for the connected device.\n\nLet me take a different approach - actually trace the data flow end-to-end by reading the actual speed.json if it exists.\n\nLet me also check: does `speedTestRun` clear `connectFullResultArea` before running? Looking at the code... `speedTestRun` only clears `speedResultArea` (line 909), not `connectFullResultArea`. But `connectSpeedTestRun` clears `connectSpeedResultMini` (line 1112), not `connectFullResultArea`.\n\nSo the stale function results in `connectFullResultArea` persist! That's a bug — but it's in the \"连接设备\" tab, not the standalone speed test.\n\nLet me also check if there's a separate rendering path for the \"高级功能\" speed test tab. Looking at includes/advanced.html:\n\nOK I need to look at this more carefully. Let me check the actual rendered page to understand which \"speed test\" the user is seeing.\n\nActually, the user said \"项目 支持 范围\" with \"0 N -~-\" — this is 100% the function detection table from `renderConnectFullResults(..., 'function')`. And \"项目\" = \"功能\" in Chinese (feature). The rows look like function capability rows.\n\nThis means:\n1. User is on the \"连接设备\" sub-tab of \"高级功能\"\n2. They ran \"一键检测\" or ran function and speed tests separately  \n3. Function test ran, showed its table correctly\n4. Speed test ran but produced empty data (no limit.json → run_all_tests returns [])\n5. Speed section appended \"测试总数: 0\" after the function table\n\nThe solution:\n1. Make the error clearer when speed can't run (missing limit data)\n2. Clear the area before appending, or better, group by test type\n\nLet me look at the data directory to see if there's any speed.json cached in old format. Actually, let me also check whether `advanced_speed_status` might be returning old cached data that the frontend calls separately.\n\nLet me check the actual page source for the advanced speed test path to understand all the rendering paths.\n\nActually, I think the simplest and most productive approach is: \n1. Check if the data directory has old-format speed cache\n2. Check all rendering paths for speed results\n3. Fix the by_zoom overwrite bug too\n4. Make sure failed/empty results show clearly\n\nLet me just do that.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":"先查缓存数据和所有渲染路径。"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_xZfiQxjyGWwjmcmIndOS3500","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cd C:\\Users\\admin\\.openclaw\\agents\\dev-factory\\astrohub && Get-ChildItem -Recurse -Filter \"speed.json\" -File | Select-Object -First 10 FullName,Length,LastWriteTime"}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_01_o9LJd2wLkmkw5xhbqVGe7909","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cd C:\\Users\\admin\\.openclaw\\agents\\dev-factory\\astrohub && Select-String -Path src/web/includes/advanced.html -Pattern \"speed|Speed\" -AllMatches | Select-Object -First 20 LineNumber,Line"}}],"api